  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Hypothesis: Breastmilk has a more powerful analgesic effect than oral sucrose to avoid
      procedural pain in preterm neonates.

      The objective is to test this hypothesis in a randomized, controlled study using a
      standardized and validated pain scale (DAN). The sample size is 21 preterm infants in each
      two groups. The main end point is a reduction of the risk to have a DAN superior to 1 from
      80% with oral sucrose to 40% with breastmilk.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
